WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.840
Hi, welcome.

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:10.080
My name is Kelly O'Briant.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:17.340
I work at RStudio as a solutions engineer, and my talk today is on showing you some configuration

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:24.360
management tools if you happen to be an analytic administrator, or as we kind of like to use

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:26.480
the term, an R admin.

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:34.200
So I'm really happy that R admin as a concept, as a role, is becoming more recognized in

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:39.119
different organizations, and people are starting to identify as this personality in different

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:40.119
organizations.

00:00:40.119 --> 00:00:46.680
But in case you don't know, an R admin is usually, as we define it, a data scientist

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:52.799
who has crawled into doing more IT-esque type work.

00:00:52.799 --> 00:00:59.500
So they take on the jobs of onboarding new tools, deploying solutions, and supporting

00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:01.900
existing standards in their organizations.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:06.820
They work closely with their IT groups to maintain, upgrade, and scale their analytic

00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:07.820
environments.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:09.300
They influence others.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:10.459
They train.

00:01:10.459 --> 00:01:13.779
They try to make things more effective in their organizations.

00:01:13.779 --> 00:01:19.980
And in general, overall, they are really passionate about making R a legitimate analytic standard

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:21.339
in their enterprise.

00:01:21.339 --> 00:01:25.639
So if you're not familiar with the R admin, you think you might be one, you want to read

00:01:25.639 --> 00:01:31.199
more about it, our Director of Solutions Engineering, Nathan Stephens, put out this blog a while

00:01:31.199 --> 00:01:38.160
ago on our R Views blog called Analytics Administration for R, so definitely check that out if you

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:42.480
are interested in reading more.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:51.699
As part of this overarching set of goals that we have for R admins, a big part of doing

00:01:51.699 --> 00:01:56.699
the work of an R admin is making R legitimate in your organizations.

00:01:56.699 --> 00:02:04.320
The R admin looks at their enterprise analytic infrastructure on a wider scale than maybe

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:06.699
a traditional data scientist would.

00:02:06.699 --> 00:02:13.320
They are aware of all of the different integration points and all of the places where R can be

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:17.779
assisting in helping manage that infrastructure.

00:02:17.779 --> 00:02:21.679
So we kind of think about these things in three different parts.

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:26.339
Your first step is to get R recognized as legitimate.

00:02:26.339 --> 00:02:31.759
If you are in the back room and IT is giving you the secret server and you've installed

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:36.759
R on it and you're kind of doing things in a shady way and giving people access to different

00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:41.619
things, like, we understand that that's going on, but we're trying to give you a framework

00:02:41.619 --> 00:02:46.160
to move out of the shadows and bring R into the light.

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:52.460
So in order to do that, we say it's important for you, the R admin, to develop competencies

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:55.240
in using our professional stack.

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:59.759
So in order to do that, you need to get hands-on experience with understanding and managing

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:01.320
R tooling.

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:08.399
And finally, you need to take the step to communicate with your IT department and get

00:03:08.399 --> 00:03:15.080
R adopted and finally, hopefully, help others in your organization so that they all get

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:21.360
to the point where various teams are all relying on integrated R-based solutions.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:22.360
So that's the ideal.

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:28.119
But we understand that this is kind of an open-ended framework, and it can be kind of

00:03:28.199 --> 00:03:32.600
frustrating and difficult to navigate because we don't have a lot of actionable steps listed

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:33.600
here.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:39.320
One of my friends, Adam, recently, in the past couple of months, started this thread

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:44.080
on Twitter that was really, really interesting where he reached out to the Rstats community

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:50.080
and said, hey, does anyone have any resources for starting conversations with IT?

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:55.399
You know, I'm struggling to make R an accepted part of our software kit.

00:03:55.399 --> 00:04:02.720
And I know Adam, and he is a very talented, capable R admin, but he's feeling stuck.

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:07.119
And so a lot of people had some really interesting ideas for him.

00:04:07.119 --> 00:04:09.160
You can go and check those out.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:17.000
But our standard advice as a place to start is that, number one, think about how, if at

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.760
all, you can get yourself a sandbox.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.239
What is a sandbox?

00:04:23.239 --> 00:04:29.880
A sandbox is any kind of server or VM that you, the R admin, has control over, completely

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:35.279
control, and you can practice getting yourself those competencies.

00:04:35.279 --> 00:04:41.720
So we have this resource available on our GitHub, which is the Solenge GitHub.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:44.600
And this one is called the Data Science Lab.

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:52.679
And it very basically takes you through assuming it assumes you have a clean EC2 AWS instance

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:57.079
to work with, but that's not a hard requirement.

00:04:57.079 --> 00:05:01.119
These commands will work on other servers as well.

00:05:01.119 --> 00:05:06.480
And it takes you through all of the parts of installing and configuring a very basic

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:07.940
pro stack.

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:12.880
So those include system dependencies and building R from source and installing packages and

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:19.440
installing our studio products and all of the various integrations that we consider

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:23.000
basic ones that are nice to have.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.239
Once you've done that manually, we would then suggest that you might be ready to explore

00:05:29.239 --> 00:05:35.619
the fire hose, which is my favorite place, docs.rstudio.com.

00:05:35.619 --> 00:05:43.239
And on docs.rstudio.com, we have all of the quick links to get to all of our admin documentation.

00:05:43.239 --> 00:05:48.519
So if you're interested in focusing on one or many of these products, this is the place

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:49.600
to go.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:54.559
Our admin docs are wonderful and they're full of many different side quests to explore in

00:05:54.559 --> 00:05:56.019
your sandboxes.

00:05:56.019 --> 00:06:03.440
So I highly recommend this site for getting started with the art of the possible.

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:09.600
So I hope at this point I've sort of explained why I'm excited about sandboxes, why I think

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.559
other people should be excited about sandboxes.

00:06:12.559 --> 00:06:20.799
Unfortunately, even though we give this advice quite a lot, we don't see a lot of people

00:06:20.799 --> 00:06:22.720
actually taking us up on it.

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:27.440
Actually building their own sandboxes and showing us what they've done and getting hands

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:28.440
on experience.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:33.640
So for my talk today, I wanted to think about, like, what kind of talk could I give that

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:39.839
would have people leaving this room being like, yeah, sandboxes!

00:06:39.839 --> 00:06:42.040
Like super excited about them.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:44.160
So that's what I've done.

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:47.920
Instead of talking about the basic sandbox, which I've sort of already done, I want to

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:51.119
talk about ultimate sandboxes.

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:56.679
And this is kind of how I develop sandboxes for my daily work as a solutions engineer.

00:06:56.679 --> 00:07:02.679
I have the privilege to be embedded on the RStudio Connect team and help them out with

00:07:02.679 --> 00:07:08.480
testing new features and figuring out how things work so that we can deliver the correct

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.760
documentation to our users.

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:18.320
So I do a lot of creating quick sandboxes that live for very short periods of time.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:21.600
But I like to save all of my work.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:28.720
So I like to create the ability to have reproducible, you know, custom environments that I can go

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:33.679
back to and visit through my GitHub if I ever needed them again.

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:38.480
And the way I do that is through configuration management tools.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:43.959
In particular, I mean, this is a bunch of the top players in that space, but there are

00:07:43.959 --> 00:07:45.160
very many.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:50.519
And it's easy to get overwhelmed by the sheer number of tools available, but my favorite

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:55.920
of the configuration management tools is Ansible.

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:00.920
Take this with a grain of salt, because I'm going to spend the next several minutes talking

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:06.920
a bunch about Ansible, but I do not believe that you should use Ansible.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:10.119
If Ansible speaks to you, more power to you.

00:08:10.119 --> 00:08:11.559
I think that's wonderful.

00:08:11.559 --> 00:08:13.440
I think it's a wonderful tool.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:15.799
Go out and learn about it.

00:08:15.799 --> 00:08:23.160
But I would suggest first checking with your IT team to see if they use a configuration

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:24.640
management tool.

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:29.720
And instead of investing your time in learning the one that I like, learn the one that they

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:35.200
use, especially if you intend on staying in your organization for any period of the next

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:40.960
several months, because that is going to really grease the wheels for helping you communicate

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:41.960
with your IT.

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:47.400
If you speak the same language as they do, if you can show that you know how to administer

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:53.719
the Rstack using the set of tools that they're comfortable with, that is a hugely powerful

00:08:53.719 --> 00:08:55.599
thing.

00:08:55.599 --> 00:09:01.400
So some things I like about Ansible are, of course, that I can stand up these servers

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:05.239
very quickly in custom ways on demand.

00:09:05.239 --> 00:09:10.559
But I also really love the rich module ecosystem that it comes with, especially the modules

00:09:10.559 --> 00:09:16.599
that they have around your basic big players in cloud compute space.

00:09:16.599 --> 00:09:23.039
So they have great modules for AWS, Azure, GCP, and they have a lot of other modules,

00:09:23.039 --> 00:09:28.440
some of which I'll talk about today, that are also nice to have and helpful.

00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:33.359
The other great thing about Ansible is that you write playbooks in YAML, and that's awesome

00:09:33.359 --> 00:09:39.500
because it is super human readable and super machine readable, and I love that.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:41.500
It's also super easy to install.

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:47.159
This is how you install it on a Mac, and then you're up and running.

00:09:47.159 --> 00:09:54.000
So I'm going to go through kind of what creating an Ansible project looks like, but as a high

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.799
level overview before I move on to the next slide, I'll say that what I'm going to talk

00:09:58.799 --> 00:10:03.000
about is kind of a nested directory of YAML.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:16.479
So the very container-ish level, you have your playbooks, and then within playbooks,

00:10:16.479 --> 00:10:21.000
you're going to have roles, and then within roles, you're going to have tasks.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.239
So I'm going to go through all of that.

00:10:23.239 --> 00:10:25.840
First with the playbook role structure.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:33.960
So this is a project that I actually did a couple weeks ago to help check out the new feature

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:41.880
that just got announced a couple minutes ago in RStudio Connect 1.7, which is support for

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:51.200
these new content management APIs that allow for programmatic deployment of content to Connect.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:56.880
So this is what my playbook role structure looks like, and I'm showing right here the

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:03.760
create sandbox playbook, and this playbook contains two roles, one for provisioning my

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:09.440
cloud infrastructure and a second one for installing RStudio Connect on it.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:16.280
So I have this playbook, create me a sandbox, and then within that playbook, different things

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:24.039
happen and I connect to it in different ways, but I have two roles, one provision, one install

00:11:24.039 --> 00:11:26.880
and configure.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:32.039
This again is about the content management APIs for programmatic deployment.

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:37.900
It's kind of a two-for-one in this talk, because I was very excited about this feature that's

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:43.880
coming into Connect, and so if you are working with your IT department and you've ever heard

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:51.119
these two questions, hey, we can't allow push button publishing or how do we implement

00:11:51.119 --> 00:11:58.280
a dev test prod setup, I believe that our new stuff around programmatic deployment will

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:02.280
be really helpful in having those types of conversations.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:08.559
There's the key resources, the RStudio user guide has just been updated with a cookbook

00:12:08.559 --> 00:12:16.919
for various server API recipes, and we also have a GitHub repo that has scripts that have

00:12:16.919 --> 00:12:23.200
examples of how to do programmatic deployment, so those, the scripts that are in this GitHub

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:32.479
repo are going to be really useful, and those are the ones that I used in this Ansible project.

00:12:32.479 --> 00:12:39.840
So again, back to roles, as I mentioned before, these roles have tasks, and the basic anatomy

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:48.520
of a task is that it's a good idea to name it, and that name should in general be relevant

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:56.119
to what the task is doing, and then you also provide the module that you want to use.

00:12:56.119 --> 00:13:02.239
And then finally, if it's applicable, you'll then provide parameters for that module and

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:04.719
plug in your variables.

00:13:04.719 --> 00:13:09.840
There are a couple of really cool things that are happening in this particular group of

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:19.400
tasks, and this is the entire role that this Ansible project uses to create and upload

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:21.380
and deploy the content.

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:29.580
So this is programmatic deployment as defined in an Ansible task listing.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:36.140
The cool things that are happening here is that I am leveraging the script module, because

00:13:36.140 --> 00:13:41.659
if you thought, like, this can't possibly be all that programmatic deployment is, that's

00:13:41.659 --> 00:13:42.659
correct.

00:13:42.659 --> 00:13:48.260
I'm leveraging some shell scripts, because I didn't want to take the time to transfer

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:52.460
all of the commands in those scripts into Ansible code.

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:58.820
So the scripts that are provided in that GitHub repo, I grabbed those out, I put them in a

00:13:58.820 --> 00:14:03.859
scripts directory, I edited them slightly to make them do what I wanted them to do,

00:14:03.859 --> 00:14:10.500
and then I'm just calling those scripts, and you can it's a really cool way to take baby

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:18.659
steps into moving any of the configuration scripts that you currently have into a more

00:14:18.659 --> 00:14:24.039
reproducible configuration management type workflow.

00:14:24.039 --> 00:14:26.539
So that's the number one cool thing I'm doing.

00:14:26.539 --> 00:14:32.460
Number two is that you can see after I've run that first task, I'm registering an output

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:40.859
object of what came out of that first script, and I'm plugging it in to the second and the

00:14:40.859 --> 00:14:42.780
third task.

00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:47.419
The final cool thing is that I remembered to use a debug statement, which is also great.

00:14:47.419 --> 00:14:50.260
I'll start moving faster.

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:51.260
Okay.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:55.539
So I talked about roles have tasks.

00:14:55.539 --> 00:15:01.140
This is the task for the deploy content role, and finally when you're ready to get up and

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:07.059
running with your playbooks, this is kind of how you run playbooks one by one.

00:15:07.059 --> 00:15:14.940
So I talked about I usually have two or maybe three playbooks that I'll run to in any given

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:20.659
Ansible project, sometimes more, but usually two or three, and one will be the playbook

00:15:20.659 --> 00:15:28.340
that installs and sets up my infrastructure, installs whatever I need on it, and the last

00:15:28.340 --> 00:15:33.059
one will be the playbook that tears everything down.

00:15:33.059 --> 00:15:36.739
This is my favorite part of Ansible sandboxing.

00:15:36.739 --> 00:15:42.340
Once you have created this thing, you now have the power to write a good read me, check

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:47.780
it all in to version control, and then burn it all to the ground, because you have the

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:54.580
ability to reproduce this environment at any time within minutes, which is awesome.

00:15:54.659 --> 00:15:59.739
So that's a little bit about how I do daily work as a solutions engineer who works with

00:15:59.739 --> 00:16:06.299
engineering teams and how I stand up these environments very quickly whenever I want,

00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:09.900
but obviously you would do things differently.

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:16.320
You have different needs for sandboxes, and so this slide kind of shows what is available

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:22.219
at a high level through docs.rfstudio.com and all of the various configurations and

00:16:22.219 --> 00:16:28.140
integrations that you could possibly use.

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:34.419
This is a little resource that I have available on our Solange GitHub, and it covers if you

00:16:34.419 --> 00:16:39.719
aren't ready for the cloud yet, but you want to start using Ansible and creating sandboxes

00:16:39.719 --> 00:16:43.700
on demand, how you might do that with VirtualBox and Vagrant.

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:49.859
It also shows kind of if you're really interested in seeing just the task structure of Ansible

00:16:50.020 --> 00:16:59.020
and how I have done the data lab sandbox inside Ansible task structure, that's available to

00:16:59.020 --> 00:17:02.659
look through here.

00:17:02.659 --> 00:17:09.380
So finally, I want to kind of end on thinking about, like, why did my talk get put in the

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:14.979
interoperability section, which kind of seems like an odd fit, but I also really like that

00:17:14.979 --> 00:17:21.839
it's in this section as well, because going back to the idea of how we get R legitimized

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:30.260
in an organization, I often hear the stock answer, like, show the value of R, like, build

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:34.739
a bunch of cool Shiny apps, and I love Shiny, I do.

00:17:34.739 --> 00:17:44.819
I'm writing a book about Shiny in production, apparently, but it isn't actionable if you

00:17:44.819 --> 00:17:49.900
don't have, like, awesome killer Shiny app ideas.

00:17:49.900 --> 00:17:58.760
So my idea for you, a better way to frame this sort of advice is to think about linking

00:17:58.760 --> 00:18:06.420
the tools that you love, R, to the tools that you know other people love in your organization.

00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:12.579
Powerful sandboxes really leverage interoperability, and we've done a lot of work at our studio

00:18:12.699 --> 00:18:20.020
to make cool integrations that are turning into true interoperability opportunities for

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:21.020
R.

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:28.540
Throughout my career, I have had, like, a lot of success helping get R legitimized by

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:35.339
putting it in terms of other people's favorite tools, and so I'll leave you with that.

00:18:35.339 --> 00:18:37.339
Thank you.

